Alright Mr. Reynaerde, I've gotten off my ass and read your thing. Unfortunately I don't think I'm the target audience for this, so don't take my word as gospel.
Let me just start out with more objective things:
Please for the love of God, add spaces between your paragraphs. While yes, I can tell them apart, it starts to run together and it drives me mad.

>S-pattern
I would have probably said "Zig-zagged" or something similar. Your original snaking descriptor was also good.

>flashed forward, to the camp
I don't think you need that comma. Adds a weird pause in reading too.

>then added, "in your own words."
Even if it isn't the start of the sentence proper, you should capitalize dialogue as if it were in this case.

>steepled his fingers, now.
I would just drop the "now."

And now for complete and utter opinion. I'm sorry to admit, but I was fairly bored until I hit the actual spaceship section. The beginning on the planet doesn't really serve much purpose, other than setting up a potential other character. (I assume that's what you meant by one staying.) The conversation afterwards with the admiral was also fairly dry, but I liked peeking into Arthur's mind. Such as the details about comfortable chairs, etc. If you're keeping that beginning, I'd also suggest a more apparent time jump between the planet and the admiral conversation. It hit me like a freight train and I had to do a double take. It makes sense logically, but felt odd.

I generally also dislike these tired "too sick of this military shit, but it's all I got" characters, but that's a minor nitpick since Arthur could easily change.

I would also maybe (depending on length of the story) change the quick character snippets. e.g. Don't tell me Bat lady is a hotshot. Describe her outward appearance, then have her act like one.

Hopefully this is of some use. I'm really bad at feedback.

hi there, fellow writefag (bugfucker) here

I guess I'm kinda echoing what other people have already said, but yeah paragraph structure is a little weird looking to me. When I read it, with how you have sentences that are sometimes only two or three words, it makes it feel like the paragraph is going -start- stop- -start- -stop-. Like you're driving a car, and you keep pressing the gas, then the brake, then the gas. It breaks up the flow and makes it feel disjointed.

One thing I always try to go after in my stories to grab someone into it, is to start with some kind of action, or setting up what's going on, why the reader should care, in the opening paragraph.

And as far as describing weird shit the characters in your world are familiar with but we as an audience aren't, I think you just gotta world-build more. I personally like elaborate descriptions of what things are, how do they sound? what do they smell like? whats the general opinion of the thing? etc etc

I dunno if that made any sense, I'm not a professional writer, but these are things I consider when I post stuff. I am interested in seeing where this goes by the way, it just needs to be refined some more.

Other anons have covered the technical side of things much better than I could have, so I'll just touch on the content.

First off, the opening sequence doesn't really seem to mesh with the rest of the story very well. It's hard to see how being trapped on a planet for six years with a couple of dead friends (?) is going to have much of a bearing on his future growth as a newly-minted captain because they're about as far apart as you can get. As >>26106222 said, it runs the risk of turning into sufferporn.

This isn't to say that Arthur shouldn't have an unfortunate past in his naval career, but I think it would have been better if it was something with more direct parallels to what he's going through in the story's present. Something like being an exemplary XO on a small ship that went down because he made a decision based on limited information that turned out to be the wrong call, and he blames himself for it. You could work the loss of a hand into it as well, perhaps his arm was badly burned while rescuing a trapped crewman and bringing them to an escape pod and by the time he got to a medical team it was too late to save it.

Something like that would have a direct impact on how he approaches and grows into his new role, because it's the same job he 'failed' at back then instead of being something completely alien to life as a senior officer on a starship's bridge.

Everything past the opening was solid though, you did a good job of channelling a slightly rough around the edges Star Trek. I definitely want to see how you're going to develop the Splendid's motley crew; I think it will be important going forwards not to forget about them and lean too heavily onto one or two characters - having the bridge feel alive and staffed with actual people instead of cardboard cutouts is a key thing in these kinds of stories.

The 'useless counsellors feeling vague emotions' bit got a chuckle out of me, too. Going to be keeping an eye out for updates for this.

But we are enjoying it, we've been enjoying it. I've got a moment finally, unlike yesterday as I'd hoped. I'm reading through the WKW update now (have it up innatab). It has some mechanical issues, but it's an unrevised draft, that's to be expected. There's no One Punch Man method to writing, not even for the pros, it's a process. The process part is what you become better at with time and throughput, and it's something like 70% revision, 10% carefully taking critique onboard ('cause let's be real, critique isn't always good), etc. That's just the way the game's always been played, dude.

Right off the bat, I feel like you're setting a mood that'll carry this chapter, maybe even this part of the story. There's not a lot of dialogue, but that's by design. Everyone's tight-lipped and just going about their routines. To add affectation and spice things up, I'm looking for some sweet, sweet body language, but I don't see much. Try revisiting those scenes in your mind's eye, look at what your characters are doing as they perform their roles. I need to keep reading it to say anything more just yet. Don't mind the mechanical issues, they're just there to get sorted out in another draft.

I think the AFaW rewrite placed you in a purely mechanical mindset, and you probably FEEL like it's made your writing equally mechanical. You write intimacy and expression well, and I think that's why writing Anya the first time was fun; she offers avenues of expression human characters don't have. Exploring and presenting human expression through feathers is a lot of fun. By now, you've written AFaW from S to the present several times, and your fatigue over it is understandable. I'll contrib. soon, too. You've got a lot of ideas waiting in the wings, and they're not all raptors.
